	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />You should find some links to 6502 documents on the main page. That is the programming language of the NES, if you do not know. How exactly to make the 6502 tell the NES to do things, there are a few document on that. NESTech, by y0shi, is really technical, but it's pretty much the reference that everyone looks at when they need to know about an aspect of the NES. I hear that NES101 is a good one (Though I have never read it), and that's a tutorial, unlike NESTech. If you come across GBAguy's tutorials, they aren't accurate at all, but they get you at least inch off the ground.
<br />
<br />Oh, and I prefer to use WLA-DX, though most people here use CC65, for an assembler.
<br />
<br />As to why you should program the NES, why were you wondering how to, if you didn't know why you should?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
